{
  "text": "Poisson distribution is used because of the existence of the hurdle. As a result zero counts need not to be modelled by the count process. The introduction of the error term \ue0ca i is meant to capture unobserved heterogeneity and is the crux to allow for correlation between the first and second step. [CITATION_1] assumes that \u03b5 i and \ue0ca i are bivariate normal distributed with expectation (0, 0), variance (1, \u03c3 2 ) and correlation \u03c1. An implicit assumption of [CITATION_2] is that the not completely observed health indicator z i is an important driving force in the determination of the frequency of doctor visits. To make this explicit, I add this factor to the specification and collect the other explanatory variables in the vector w i.",
  "citation_candidates": [
